<div id="review_3812899301" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3812899301" />
    <a title="Bradley" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/115411988-bradley"><img alt="Bradley" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1625019283p2/115411988.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3812899301?book_show_action=true">May 12, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Bradley" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Bradley" href="/user/show/115411988-bradley">Bradley</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3812899301" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer10430162349658632991">The Bronx in Burning provides a raw view of the relationship between the Yankees and their home town in the summer of &apos;77 as the explosive turmoil between Reggie Jackson, baseball&apos;s richest star and Billy Martin it&apos;s most volatile manager, perfectly mirrored the combustible frustration of a city in disrepair. <br/><br/>A blackout, a long night of looting, massive police layoffs and protests, a rapidly declining economy, a cutthroat mayoral race, a brutal serial killer (the son of Sam) and a raging conflag</span>
  <span id="freeText10430162349658632991" style="display:none">The Bronx in Burning provides a raw view of the relationship between the Yankees and their home town in the summer of '77 as the explosive turmoil between Reggie Jackson, baseball's richest star and Billy Martin it's most volatile manager, perfectly mirrored the combustible frustration of a city in disrepair. <br /><br />A blackout, a long night of looting, massive police layoffs and protests, a rapidly declining economy, a cutthroat mayoral race, a brutal serial killer (the son of Sam) and a raging conflagration all exploded as the Yankees (spoiler alert) won their first World Series in 15 years. <br /><br />My only hangup, hence the 4 stars, is the lack of balance between baseball and civics, this book is about 80% of the ladder and 20% of the former. That's just me being nitpicky. Otherwise, I highly recommend it.</span>
  <a data-text-id="10430162349658632991" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
